```java
public final void translate(CharSequence input, Writer out) throws IOException {
    if (out == null) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("The Writer must not be null");
    }
    if (input == null) {
        return;
    }
    int pos = 0;
    int len = input.length(); // use char length, not code point count
    while (pos < len) {
        int consumed = translate(input, pos, out); // returns chars consumed
        if (consumed == 0) {
            // no translation for this code point, just output it
            char[] c = Character.toChars(Character.codePointAt(input, pos));
            out.write(c);
            pos += Character.charCount(Character.codePointAt(input, pos));
        } else {
            // translator consumed consumed chars
            pos += consumed;
        }
    }
}
```

That is the standard fix. Note: In the original buggy code, they had a for loop to handle multiple code points if consumed > 1, but since consumed is chars consumed, we simply add it. Also, we need to ensure that `Character.codePointAt` works correctly with surrogate pairs, and `Character.charCount` gives the correct number of chars.

